{
  "card_id": "us_dollar_index_dxy_bias_framework",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "US Dollar Index (DXY) Bias Framework",
  "aliases": [
    "Dollar Bias Pairing Framework",
    "dollar bias pairing framework",
    "DXY Bias",
    "dxy bias"
  ],
  "school": "Order Flow",
  "definition": "A currency pair selection framework using the DXY's trend state to determine which forex pair or currency future to trade: a trending DXY is paired with the strongest opposing currency, while a consolidating DXY shifts focus to pairing non-dollar currencies of opposite bias.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Classify DXY as bullish trending, bearish trending, or consolidating by reviewing its daily candle closures and trend structure.",
    "If DXY is bullish trending, scan the other major currencies and select the most bearish one to pair against it (e.g. trade EUR/USD when EUR is the weakest).",
    "If DXY is bearish trending, scan the other major currencies and select the most bullish one to pair against it (e.g. trade USD/JPY when JPY is the strongest).",
    "If DXY is consolidating (often after large expansion or at a higher time frame key level), exclude DXY and pair the strongest non-dollar currency with the weakest non-dollar currency.",
    "If no clearly opposing currency exists, pair a trending currency with a consolidating one, accepting a weaker resulting trend.",
    "For futures-only traders when DXY is trending, simply trade the single currency future most opposite to DXY's direction."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "The framework prioritizes maximum expansion by pairing the strongest with the weakest currency, treating each forex pair as a fraction of two relative strengths. When DXY trends, it is always one side of the pair; when DXY consolidates or retraces (anticipated after expansion into HTF key levels), the trader rotates into exotic or cross pairs. Multiple acceptable choices typically exist on a given dollar-bias day; the priority is eliminating currencies that are too neutral (e.g. JPY when not bullish enough) rather than finding a single perfect asset.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Pairing the dollar with another trending currency in the same relative direction, which produces a consolidating pair instead of an expansive trend.",
    "Pairing a trending currency with a consolidating one when a true opposite exists, settling for a weaker trend than necessary.",
    "Continuing to pair against DXY when DXY itself is consolidating, instead of rotating to non-dollar crosses.",
    "Forcing a trade on a currency (e.g. JPY) that is not sufficiently strong or weak relative to the others on that day."
  ],
